'''Woollyback''' is a dialect term used in [[Liverpool]], England for a non-Liverpudlian

The term usually refers to a person from the neighbouring towns of [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]], [[Widnes]], [[Warrington]] and [[Wigan]], as these places each share a similar [[English English#Northern English|accent]] to each other, though substantially different from Liverpool's '[[scouse]]'. The term may also be used to simply refer to somebody that is not from Liverpool.  Originally it was a nickname for those people who worked on the [[:Category:Liverpool Docks|docks in Liverpool]], who used to carry the wool for export onto the ships and were therefore called 'woollybacks'. An alternative origin comes from the time when passengers crossing the Mersey to attend markets in Liverpool would be charged per foot on board. Poor farmers would gather their animals onto their backs, so to minimise the charge, hence Woollybacks.

Also used as a general term of abuse by Lancastrians for people from West Yorkshire. {{fact}}

